<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 8.1.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder"><h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. Summary of the Competency
</h3>
  <p><em>Community expertise and perspectives</em> ensure the health and wellbeing of MCH populations through respectful professional collaboration and shared decision making. Partnerships with community-led organizations recognize the capabilities, traditions, and knowledge that all participants bring when engaged in program planning, implementation, evaluation, and policy activities. These partnerships help MCH leaders connect with various community members to ensure appropriate input from service recipients.</p>
<p>Historically in the field of MCH, the concept of family-centered care was developed within communities of parents, professionals, and health professionals working with children and youth with special health care needs (CYSHCN), with the goal that all care is received in family-centered, comprehensive, coordinated systems. CYSHCN have or are at increased risk for chronic physical, developmental, behavioral, or emotional conditions. They also require health and related services of a type or amount beyond that required by children generally.</p>
<p>The field now recognizes that individuals with self-determination also provide critical insights and perspectives to the successful development of effective policies, practices, and care delivery. These individuals have personal experience in a system of care and communicate their own interests, desires, needs and rights.</p>
<p>Family perspectives and individual, self-determination expertise constitute two distinct, valued perspectives that each provide unique knowledge to the field. Family members, individuals with self-determination, and others with community expertise can serve as faculty, staff, and consultants to provide interdisciplinary teams with their perspective of receiving care and services. Community experts as leaders and teachers are invaluable to training programs, clinical services, and other public health programs.</p>
<p>The key to effective partnerships with community experts entails:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Shared decision making, involving individuals with self-determination and/or the family, in planning and implementing activities.</li>
  <li>Responding to the needs of community members using a capabilities-based approach.</li>
  <li>Recognizing individual agency in decision-making during transition age, and across the lifespan.</li>
  <li>Connecting community members to needed services.</li>
  <li>Acknowledging that broader systems of care and community circumstances greatly impact individuals requiring additional health services and developmental disabilities.</li>
</ul>
