<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graduation-cap"></i> <strong>Learn More.</strong> Outlining knowledge and skills that support the competency.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p>The MCH Leadership Competencies describe the necessary knowledge and skills (foundational and advanced) designed to support and promote MCH leadership. These areas will be further explored in the next section of the module.</p>
  <h3>KNOWLEDGE AREAS</h3>
  <p>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <ul>
    <li index="0">The expertise of individuals with practical knowledge in developing programs and services.</li>
    <li>The person-centered care perspective at the individual, organizational, and systems level in MCH policies, programs, or practice.</li>
    <li>The family-centered care perspective at the individual, organizational, and systems level in MCH policies, programs, or practice.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>SKILLS</h3>
  <p><strong>Foundational. </strong>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will be able to:  </p>
  <ul>
    <ol>
      <li>Seek and apply input from individuals with community expertise in the design and delivery of clinical or public health services, program planning, materials development, program activities, and evaluation. Also, ensure appropriate compensation for contributions.</li>
      <li>Provide training, mentoring, and leadership opportunities to individuals with community expertise and community members to serve on advisory committees or task forces. Furthermore, seek guidance and insights from these groups to inform program and care development.</li>
      <li>Demonstrate shared decision-making among individuals, families, and professionals using a capabilities-based approach to strengthen practices, programs, or policies that affect MCH populations.</li>
      <li>Assess and tailor recommendations to social, educational, and community circumstances affecting individuals with community expertise.</li>
      <li>Recognize and support the unique backgrounds of individuals and families.</li>
      <li>Recognize that organizational and system-level policies and practices may impact individuals with community expertise as well as acknowledge the role that these individuals can play in influencing policy and practice.</li>
    </ol>
    </ul>
<p><strong>Advanced</strong>. Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will be able to:    </p>
<ol>
  <li index="0">Collaborate with organizations that are led by individuals with community expertise to build and deepen involvement across all MCH programs.</li>
  <li index="1">Use feedback from individuals with community expertise and community members, obtained through focus groups, surveys, community advisory boards, and other mechanisms as part of the project's continuous improvement efforts. Monitor and assess the program overall for effectiveness of partnerships between professionals and individuals with community expertise.</li>
  <li index="2">Ensure that perspectives from individuals with community expertise are actively informing the development, implementation, and critical evaluation of MCH research, clinical practice, programs, and policies.</li>
  <li index="3">Assist health care professionals, organizations, and health plans to develop, implement, and evaluate models of family-professional partnerships and direct partnerships with individuals with self-determination.</li>
  <li index="4">Incorporate content about partnerships between individuals with community expertise and professionals into health professions and continuing education curricula and assess the impact of this training on professional skills, programs, and policies.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="evidenceBorder"><h3><i class="mch-compass-2"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-compass-3.jpg" alt="Image of Compass" class="right ppic" />RELATE. Linking to Related Concepts and Competencies</h3>
<p>This  competency relates to <strong>Systems Integration</strong></p>
<p><em>Systems integration</em> involves being able to use systems thinking to leverage existing resources to address complex problems. Systems thinking looks at the broader context — the system — in which a problem exists and the interrelationships and feedback loops that are at work, rather than trying to break the problem down into smaller pieces in an attempt to find a solution.</p>
<p>Tools such as systems thinking, mapping, and improvement methods help Title V professionals build expertise for cross-sector collaboration.</p>
<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graduation-cap"></i> <strong>Learn More.</strong> Expanding on the related concept/competency.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p>As the need for public health programs in general increases and funding becomes harder to secure, it's essential that public health staff have the ability to integrate systems across current and planned programming. Successful systems integration addresses community conditions influencing health, engages stakeholders and community members, aligns investments, and demonstrates collaboration on the use of data.</p>
  <p>To apply systems integration, MCH and other public health staff will want to develop the following competencies:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>They should become familiar with system science terminology and methods, and the extent to which health-related applications pertain to current programs and public health challenges.</li>
    <li>They should learn how to identify complex problems for which different types of system science methods are useful.</li>
    <li>They should be able to identify new leverage points for change within MCH and public health systems.</li>
    <li>They should be able to use system diagrams to describe and study complex system problems across multiple stakeholders to facilitate collective impact and improve outcomes.</li>
    <li>And they should be aware of the opportunities and challenges that health reform brings to MCH and public health system integration.</li>
  </ul>
  </div>
  
	</div>
    
